Review dimension: Security
Severity: critical
File: Services/FileService.cs:160-167 (UploadAsync); Controllers/FilesController.cs:53-64 (Upload)
Title: Arbitrary file write / path traversal via unsanitized uploaded file name

Finding:
...

Fix instructions (follow exactly; make targeted, minimal changes):
In `Services/FileService.cs`, harden `UploadAsync(string relativeDirPath, IFormFile file)` so the client-supplied filename cannot escape the home root. After resolving and creating the directory: (1) derive a safe leaf name with `var leafName = Path.GetFileName(file.FileName);` (this strips any leading directories, `..` segments, drive roots, and absolute paths); (2) reject empty or invalid names — `if (string.IsNullOrWhiteSpace(leafName) || leafName.IndexOfAny(Path.GetInvalidFileNameChars()) >= 0) throw new ArgumentException("Invalid file name");`; (3) compute `var path = Path.GetFullPath(Path.Combine(dir, leafName));` and re-apply the SAME containment check used by `SafeResolve` (i.e., `path == Root` or `path.StartsWith(Root + Path.DirectorySeparatorChar, StringComparison.Ordinal)`), throwing `ArgumentException("Invalid file name")` if it fails; (4) only then `await using var fs = File.Create(path); await file.CopyToAsync(fs);`. Optionally expose a small private helper (e.g. `ResolveChildPath(dir, leafName)`) so the containment logic isn't duplicated. Then, in `Controllers/FilesController.cs`, change the `Upload` response path construction to use the same sanitized leaf: replace `file.FileName` with `System.IO.Path.GetFileName(file.FileName ?? string.Empty)` in both branches of `var resultPath = string.IsNullOrEmpty(dir) ? ... : $"{dir}/{...}";`. Finally add regression tests in `TestProject.Tests/Services/FileServiceTests.cs` that assert `UploadAsync("", FormFileFactory.CreateFormFile("../../escape.txt", "x"))` and an absolute/rooted filename both throw `ArgumentException` and that no file is created outside the home root (e.g., assert `File.Exists(Path.Combine(root, "..", "escape.txt"))` is false).

